</simplesect>
<anchor id="mempool_8h_1mempool"/> <simplesect kind="par"><title>Detailed Description </title><para>A memory slab is a kernel object that allows memory blocks to be dynamically allocated from a designated memory region. All memory blocks in a memory slab have a single fixed size, allowing them to be allocated and released efficiently and avoiding memory fragmentation concerns. <linebreak/>
 A memory slab has the following key properties:<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>The block size of each block, measured in bytes. It must be at least 4N bytes long, where N is greater than 0.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>The number of blocks available for allocation. It must be greater than zero.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>A buffer that provides the memory for the memory slab’s blocks. It must be at least “block size” times “number of blocks” bytes long. The memory slab’s buffer must be aligned to an N-byte boundary, where N is a power of 2 larger than 2 (i.e. 4, 8, 16, …). To ensure that all memory blocks in the buffer are similarly aligned to this boundary, the block size must also be a multiple of N.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
</simplesect>
